ent recognition tradition not only casts light on various literary and theological features of the chapter but also shapes the way the appearances function in the wider narrative. By utilizing recognition, Luke 24 generates cognitive, affective, commissive, and hermeneutical functions for the characters internal to the narrative and for the audience. The result is a compelling climax to Luke’s Gospel that resonates with Luke’s wider literary and theological themes. This work offers a compelling analysis of the Luke’s Gospel in the ancient literary context in light of the ancient technique of recognition that will appeal to those interested in narrative approaches to the New Testament or the interpretation of the New Testament in the wider literary milieu.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAuferstehung. 4aLukasevangelium. 4aNarrative Exegese. 4aNeues Testament. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aClassical Literature.  aGospel of Luke.  aNarrative Approaches.  aNew Testament.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z97831111757820 cEPUBz97831107739100 cprintz978311077320040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311077374340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110773743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110773743/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK